1 scale simulation for the no-math crowd

Beyond compositionally in high throughput sequencing; estimating the importance of scale in data analysis

  • HTS is scale invariant

    • same library different total counts
    • the same results from instruments with differing outputs
    • process of making libraries ensures that equal numbers of molecules go in each sample
      • within measurement error
      • erases scale differences
      • all scale information is simply measurement error or intrinsic scale
      • illumina technical notes (https://support-docs.illumina.com/SHARE/ClusterOptimize/Content/SHARE/ClusterOptimize/OptimalClusterDensity.htm) recommend cluster densities between 170k/mm2 to 1400k/mm2 depending on instrument. Clustering higher results in less or no data, clustering lower results in less data. Cluster density is a function of the input DNA concentration
    • normalizations assume that the output count is proportional to the input count
      • in error
    • log-ratio approaches assume that the input and output are proportionally related
    • the size of the underlying system is important - extrinsic scale
      • cMyc KO are 3X the size of wt cells in terms of transcriptional abundance
      • the vaginal microbiome differs by two orders of magnitude in absolute abundance
      • wt and KO cells often have different growth rates
      • ABx can reduce total microbial load
      • different cell types have different transcriptional capacities (SS)
      • differing genome and plasmid content
    • despite this, scale is ignored
    • A proper model estimates both the difference in abundance (location) and the difference in size (scale)
    • tools estimate measurement error (shot noise) using NB or Dir models post sequencing
      • location estimates derived from this
    • tools do not account for differences in extrinsic or intrinsic scale
      • cannot measure directly, but can estimate it’s effect post-hoc on results

We will denote a sequence count dataset as an \(D \times N\) matrix \(Y\), with elements \(Y_{dn}\) denoting the number of sequenced DNA molecules mapping to the \(d\)-th entity (e.g., taxa or gene) in the \(n\)-th sample. A key element of SRI is that the observed data is an imperfect measurement of some underlying biological system which we denote \(W\) and call a . Like \(Y\), \(W\) is a \(D \times N\) matrix. Unlike \(Y\), the elements \(W_{dn}\) denote the true (as opposed to measured) amount of entity \(d\) in the biological system from which the \(n\)-th sample was taken. To preempt potential conclusion, we note that the notion of is flexible: in microbiota studies is not limited to bacterial cell count but could be alternative notions such as colony forming units (CFUs) or cellular concentration in a medium. We think of \(W\) as being composed of scale (i.e., summed amounts) and composition (i.e., relative amounts). We denote the scale of the system as an \(N\)-vector \(W^{\perp}\) with elements \(W^{\perp}_{n}=\sum_{d=1}^{D}W_{dn}\). We denote the composition of the system as a \(D\times N\) matrix \(W^{\parallel}\) with elements \(W^{\parallel}_{dn}=W_{dn}/W^{\perp}_{n}\). It follows that the composition and scale of the system uniquely determine the system via: \(W_{dn}=W^{\parallel}_{dn}W^{\perp}_{n}\). Throughout this paper, we use hat notation to denote an estimate of a quantity (e.g., \(\hat{W}\) is an estimate of \(W\)) .

We can let \(W\) be the data matrix or table that describes the system we want to measure. This systems contains \(N\) samples and \(D\) parts where each part is a gene, species, etc and we denote the \(d\)-th part in the \(n\)-th sample as \(W_{dn}\). The actual data is composed of both proportional (relative) and scale (size) information, such that \(W = W^{\parallel}\) and \(W^{\perp}\). It is possible that the relative and size information can vary independently. For example, the total number of RNA molecules in a cell may vary by type, but the relative amounts of many of them may be constant; alternatively the total number of molecules may be the same, but the relative proportions may change. Of course, there could be a mixture of both possibilities as well.

We can directly estimate \(W^{\parallel}) by taking a random sample and determining the counts of the parts in the sample. The properties of this measure \(Y\) should be well known, and the accuracy with which \(Y\) is a good estimate of \(W^{\parallel}\) is determined by the number of samples. (Wu 2022).

So in formal terms, the system we want to measure is a set of N samples with D parts (genes, species, etc) contained in a matrix or data table W. The observed data is in a matrix Y, which contains the same We incorporate measurement uncertainty as uncertainty around the observed value We incorporate scale uncertainty as uncertainty around the correction used (Gx) - contant uncertainty increases dispersion - different amounts of uncertainty increases dispersion and moves the center

Results - examples: - Figure 1 - what is uncertainty and how do we include it

  • \(Y\) is a point estimate of the data and under-samples the true underlying distribution because of sparse random sampling.

  • (W^{}) is a more accurate estimate of the sampling uncertainty derived from Dirichlet Monte-Carlo sampling to ‘fill-in’ and provide a posterior distribution of plausible values based on the point estimates

  • \(W^\) can be estimated for a given scale by adding scale uncertainty \(W^{\perp}\) with \(\gamma\) = 1. This has the result of further smoothing and broadening the distribution to account for the uncertainty in the scale of the system from which the data was drawn.

data(selex)

selex.clr <- apply(selex+0.5, 2, function(x) log2(x) - mean(log2(x)))

par(mfrow=c(3,1))
 plot(density(selex.clr['A:D:G:E',1:7]), xlim=c(1,9), col='red', main='Point Estimate', xlab='clr Value')
  points(density(selex.clr['A:D:G:E',8:14]), col='blue', type='l')
  segments(selex.clr['A:D:G:E',1:7], 0.05, selex.clr['A:D:G:E',1:7], 0, col='red')
  segments(selex.clr['A:D:G:E',8:14], 0.05, selex.clr['A:D:G:E',8:14], 0, col='blue')
 
  conds <- c(rep('N',7), rep('S',7))
  
  x <- aldex.clr(selex, conds, gamma=NULL, mc.samples=128, verbose=F)
## conditions vector supplied
## operating in serial mode
## computing center with all features
  aldex.plotFeature(x, 'A:D:G:E', pooledOnly=T, densityOnly=T)

  x <- aldex.clr(selex, conds, gamma=1, mc.samples=128, verbose=F)
## conditions vector supplied
## operating in serial mode
## aldex.scaleSim: adjusting samples to reflect scale uncertainty.
    aldex.plotFeature(x, 'A:D:G:E', pooledOnly=T, densityOnly=T)

Practically how does this affect us? - motivating example, effect size is non-linearly related to growth rate because of scale compression in selex (scale makes seq and gr linearly related) - too many significant genes in a simple transcriptome (reduces n significant) - asymmetry of standard genes in metatranscriptome (moves centre)

Discussion Scale is important and overlooked - solves some issues with HTS that are ignored Scale robustness should be an important part of data analysis Sca
